<node CREATED="1728658310113" ID="ID_764804701" MODIFIED="1728659357840" TEXT="##### PROMPT:&#xa;``list all software patterns in a markdown table with header: &quot;Category&quot;(One of Creational, Structural, Behabioral), &quot;Pattern&quot;, &quot;Description&quot;, &quot;Use Case&quot;``&#xa;&#xa;| Category | Pattern | Description | Use Case |&#xa;| --- | --- | --- | --- |&#xa;| Creational | Singleton | Ensures that only one instance of a class is created. | Database connections, logging objects, session management |&#xa;| Creational | Factory Method | Provides an interface for creating objects in a superclass, while allowing subclasses to alter the type of objects created. | Object  creation, dependency injection |&#xa;| Creational | Abstract Factory | Provides an interface for creating families of related or dependent objects without specifying their concrete classes. | Database connections, logging objects, session management |&#xa;| Creational | Builder | Separates object construction from its representation, allowing the same constructor to create different representations. | Complex object  creation, dependency injection |&#xa;| Creational | Prototype | Creates new objects by copying an existing prototype. | Object cloning, serialization, reflection |&#xa;| Structural | Adapter | Allows classes with incompatible interfaces to work together by wrapping its own interface around that of another class. | Interoperability  between libraries or frameworks, compatibility with legacy code |&#xa;| Structural | Bridge | Decouples an abstraction from its implementation so that the two can vary independently. | Code reuse, plugin architecture |&#xa;| Structural | Composite | Combines objects in a tree structure to represent part-whole hierarchies. | Data structures, object composition |&#xa;| Structural | Decorator | Attaches additional responsibilities to an object dynamically. | Extending functionality at runtime, code reuse |&#xa;| Structural | Facade | Provides a simplified interface to a complex subsystem. | Hiding complexity, simplifying interaction |&#xa;| Structural | Flyweight | Reuses existing objects to reduce memory usage and improve performance. | Data caching, web page optimization |&#xa;| Structural | Proxy | Provides an alternate access to an object to control access, log requests, or add additional functionality. | Authentication, security, logging |&#xa;| Behavioral | Chain of Responsibility | Passes a request between a chain of objects until one handles it. | Exception handling, error recovery |&#xa;| Behavioral | Command | Encapsulates a request as an object, allowing parameters to be passed and received via queues or logs. | Functionality delegation, undo/redo |&#xa;| Behavioral | Interpreter | Implements a specialized language and evaluates the meaning of sentences in that language. | Domain-specific languages, scripting  languages |&#xa;| Behavioral | Iterator | Provides a way to access the elements of an aggregate object sequentially without exposing its underlying representation. | Data traversal, streaming data |&#xa;| Behavioral | Mediator | Defines an interface for communicating between classes and allows them to be loosely coupled. | Event-driven architecture, message brokers |&#xa;| Behavioral | Memento | Provides the ability to restore an object to a previous state. | Undo/redo functionality, version control |&#xa;| Behavioral | Observer | Defines a one-to-many dependency between objects so that when one object changes state, all its dependents are notified automatically. | Data binding, change notification |&#xa;| Behavioral | State | Allows an object to alter its behavior when its state changes. | Finite state machine, workflow management |&#xa;| Behavioral | Strategy | Encapsulates an algorithm inside a class, allowing it to be easily changed at runtime. | Algorithms, extensibility |&#xa;| Behavioral | Template Method | Defines the skeleton of an algorithm in a method, letting subclasses provide the specific behavior for certain steps. | Code reuse, extension |&#xa;| Behavioral | Visitor | Separates an algorithm from an object structure by visiting each element in the structure. | Data traversal, code generation |&#xa;&#xa;**Note:** Some software patterns may overlap between categories or have different names depending on the language or framework being used.&#xa;">
